            },
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Lee Kuan Yew"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " was born in Singapore in 1923. He was educated at Raffles College, Singapore and Fitzwilliam College, Cambridge, England."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "attrs": {
              "dir": "ltr"
            },
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "He was called to the Bar, Middle Temple, London, in 1950 and practised law in Singapore. He became advisor to several trade unions."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "attrs": {
              "dir": "ltr"
            },
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "In 1954, he was a founder of the People's Action Party and was Secretary General up to 1992."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      "imageAlt": "Portrait of Singapore first prime minister, Mr Lee Kuan Yew",
      "imageSrc": "/images/past-ministers/lee-kuan-yew.png"
    },
    {
      "type": "prose",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "attrs": {
            "dir": "ltr"
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "He became Singapore's Prime Minister in 1959, serving successive terms until he resigned in November 1990, when he was appointed Senior Minister by Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "attrs": {
            "dir": "ltr"
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "He was re-appointed again after the 1991, 1997 and 2001 general elections."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "attrs": {
            "dir": "ltr"
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "He was appointed Minister Mentor by Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong in August 2004, and was reappointed again after the 2006 general elections"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "attrs": {
            "dir": "ltr"
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "He stepped down as Minister Mentor in May 2011, and was appointed Senior Advisor to the Government of Singapore Investment Corporation."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "attrs": {
            "dir": "ltr"
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Mr Lee passed away on 23 March 2015."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
